.SH NAME
Bitcoin::Crypto::Transaction \- Bitcoin transaction instance
.SH SYNOPSIS
.IX Header "SYNOPSIS"
.Vb 1
\&        use Bitcoin::Crypto qw(btc_utxo btc_transaction);
\&
\&        # extract unspent transaction outputs from the previous transaction
\&        btc_utxo\->extract([hex => $serialized_previous_tx]);
\&
\&        # create transaction from its serialized form
\&        my $tx = btc_transaction\->from_serialized([hex => $serialized_this_tx]);
\&
\&        # this will verify the transaction and throw an exception if it is not correct
\&        $tx\->verify;
\&
\&        # dump the transaction in readable format
\&        print $tx\->dump;
.Ve
.SH DESCRIPTION
.IX Header "DESCRIPTION"
Transaction support in Bitcoin::Crypto is provided on best\-effort basis. The
goal is not to reimplement Bitcoin Core, which would most likely lead to
security issues, but rather to provide means to manipulate a set of well\-known
standard transaction types. Widely used \f(CW\*(C`P2PKH\*(C'\fR, \f(CW\*(C`P2SH\*(C'\fR, their SegWit
counterparts, \f(CW\*(C`P2TR\*(C'\fR and \f(CW\*(C`P2MS\*(C'\fR are thoroughly tested and should be safe to
use. Still, keep "DISCLAIMER" in Bitcoin::Crypto::Manual in mind.
.PP
See "Transactions" in Bitcoin::Crypto::Manual for details and guidelines.
.SH INTERFACE
.IX Header "INTERFACE"
.SS Attributes
.IX Subsection "Attributes"
\fIversion\fR
.IX Subsection "version"
.PP
Integer containing version of the transaction. By default \f(CW1\fR.
.PP
\&\fIAvailable in the constructor\fR.
.PP
\fIinputs\fR
.IX Subsection "inputs"
.PP
The array reference of transaction inputs (Bitcoin::Crypto::Transaction::Input).
.PP
It\*(Aqs better to use "add_input" instead of pushing directly to this array.
.PP
\fIoutputs\fR
.IX Subsection "outputs"
.PP
The array reference of transaction outputs (Bitcoin::Crypto::Transaction::Output).
.PP
It\*(Aqs better to use "add_output" instead of pushing directly to this array.
.PP
\fIlocktime\fR
.IX Subsection "locktime"
.PP
Integer containing locktime of the transaction. By default \f(CW0\fR.
.PP
\&\fIAvailable in the constructor\fR.
.PP
\fIblock\fR
.IX Subsection "block"
.PP
An optional instance of Bitcoin::Crypto::Block. This reference is weakened.
Block may be required to do some validations when calling "verify".
.PP
\&\fIAvailable in the constructor\fR.
.PP
\&\fIwriter:\fR \f(CW\*(C`set_block\*(C'\fR
.PP
\&\fIpredicate:\fR \f(CW\*(C`has_block\*(C'\fR
.SS Methods
.IX Subsection "Methods"
\fInew\fR
.IX Subsection "new"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $tx = $class\->new(%args)
.Ve
.PP
This is a standard Moo constructor, which can be used to create the object. It
takes arguments specified in "Attributes".
.PP
Returns class instance.
.PP
\fIadd_input\fR
.IX Subsection "add_input"
.PP
.Vb 2
\&        $object = $object\->add_input($input_object)
\&        $object = $object\->add_input(%args)
.Ve
.PP
Adds a new input to the transaction.
.PP
If a single scalar is passed, it must be a constructed object of Bitcoin::Crypto::Transaction::Input.
.PP
Otherwise expects a hash of arguments passed to "new" in Bitcoin::Crypto::Transaction::Input.
.PP
Returns itself (for chaining).
.PP
\fIadd_output\fR
.IX Subsection "add_output"
.PP
.Vb 2
\&        $object = $object\->add_output($output_object)
\&        $object = $object\->add_output(%args)
.Ve
.PP
Same as "add_input", but adds an output (Bitcoin::Crypto::Transaction::Output).
.PP
\fIto_serialized\fR
.IX Subsection "to_serialized"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $serialized = $object\->to_serialized(%params)
.Ve
.PP
Serializes a transaction into a bytestring.
.PP
\&\f(CW%params\fR can be any of:
.IP \(bu 4
\&\f(CW\*(C`witness\*(C'\fR
.Sp
Boolean, default \f(CW1\fR. If \f(CW0\fR is passed, forces serialization without witness
data. Note that this is a no\-op in non\-segwit transactions.
.PP
\fIfrom_serialized\fR
.IX Subsection "from_serialized"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $object = $class\->from_serialized($data, %params)
.Ve
.PP
Deserializes the bytestring \f(CW$data\fR into a transaction object.
.PP
\&\f(CW%params\fR can be any of:
.IP \(bu 4
\&\f(CW\*(C`pos\*(C'\fR
.Sp
Position for partial string decoding. Optional. If passed, must be a scalar
reference to an integer value.
.Sp
This integer will mark the starting position of \f(CW$bytestring\fR from which to
start decoding. It will be set to the next byte after end of transaction stream.
.PP
Keep in mind it\*(Aqs best to have a full set of UTXOs registered. If they are not,
an exception may be raised if a function requires full UTXO data. That
exception will contain transaction ID and output index, which should help you
fill in the blanks. See Bitcoin::Crypto::Transaction::UTXO for details.
.PP
\fIget_hash\fR
.IX Subsection "get_hash"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $hash = $object\->get_hash(%params)
.Ve
.PP
Returns the hash of the transaction, also used as its id. The return value is a
bytestring.
.PP
\&\f(CW%params\fR can be any of:
.IP \(bu 4
\&\f(CW\*(C`witness\*(C'\fR
.Sp
Whether witness data should be included in the hash. Default: false
.PP
NOTE: this method returns the hash in big endian, which is not suitable for
serialized transactions. If you want to manually encode the hash into the
transaction, you should first \f(CW\*(C`scalar reverse\*(C'\fR it.
.PP
\fItxid\fR
.IX Subsection "txid"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $txid = $object\->txid()
.Ve
.PP
Returns the transaction id as a bytestring. Same as calling "get_hash"
but always with \f(CW\*(C`witness => 0\*(C'\fR.
.PP
\fIwtxid\fR
.IX Subsection "wtxid"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $wtxid = $object\->wtxid()
.Ve
.PP
Returns the transaction witness id as a bytestring. Same as calling "get_hash"
but always with \f(CW\*(C`witness => 1\*(C'\fR.
.PP
\fIget_digest\fR
.IX Subsection "get_digest"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $digest = $object\->get_digest(%params)
.Ve
.PP
This method produces the digest of the transaction. The result is an object of
Bitcoin::Crypto::Transaction::Digest::Result class. Transaction digests can
be signed by "sign_message" in Bitcoin::Crypto::Key::Private, but for standard
transactions "sign_transaction" in Bitcoin::Crypto::Key::Private can be used
instead to skip manual work.
.PP
It always returns digest as if all verification flags were activated.
Pre\-SegWit scripts that look like SegWit (and should produce different digests)
can\*(Aqt contain any signature operations, so flags would not change the behavior
of signature checking.
.PP
\&\f(CW%params\fR can be any of:
.IP \(bu 4
\&\f(CW\*(C`signing_index\*(C'\fR
.Sp
This non\-negative integer is the index of the input being signed. Required.
.IP \(bu 4
\&\f(CW\*(C`signing_subscript\*(C'\fR
.Sp
The subscript used in digesting. It is only required for \f(CW\*(C`P2SH\*(C'\fR, \f(CW\*(C`P2WSH\*(C'\fR and
custom scripts.
.IP \(bu 4
\&\f(CW\*(C`sighash\*(C'\fR
.Sp
The sighash which should be used for the digest. By default
"SIGHASH_ALL" in Bitcoin::Crypto::Constants for pre\-taproot and
"SIGHASH_DEFAULT" in Bitcoin::Crypto::Constants for taproot.
.IP \(bu 4
\&\f(CW\*(C`taproot_ext_flag\*(C'\fR
.Sp
Taproot extension flag defined by BIP341 (integer). \f(CW0\fR (no extension) by
default.
.IP \(bu 4
\&\f(CW\*(C`taproot_ext\*(C'\fR
.Sp
Taproot extension as a bytestring. No extension by default.
.IP \(bu 4
\&\f(CW\*(C`taproot_annex\*(C'\fR
.Sp
Taproot annex defined by BIP341 as a bytestring. No annex by default.
.Sp
Caution: BIP341 warns to not use annex until the meaning of this field is
defined by a softfork.
.PP
Note that digest is implemented as a persistent object associated with the
transaction which may hold some data cached for reuse. Adding inputs and
outputs through "add_input" and "add_output" will cause this object to be
recreated, since the cache must be invalidated. If you change transaction in a
way that won\*(Aqt clear this cache and you call \f(CW\*(C`get_digest\*(C'\fR repeatedly, you may
force this by calling \f(CW\*(C`clear_digest_object\*(C'\fR.
.PP
\fIget_digest_object\fR
.IX Subsection "get_digest_object"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $digest_object = $object\->get_digest_object(%params)
.Ve
.PP
Same as "get_digest", but returns an object of
\&\f(CW\*(C`Bitcoin::Crypto::Transaction::Digest\*(C'\fR instead of a bytestring. Advanced use
only.
.PP
\fIfee\fR
.IX Subsection "fee"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $fee = $object\->fee()
.Ve
.PP
Returns the fee \- the difference between sum of input values and the sum of
output values. The fee is always zero or positive integer, but can be undefined
if the UTXOs were not registered.
.PP
\fIfee_rate\fR
.IX Subsection "fee_rate"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $fee_rate = $object\->fee_rate()
.Ve
.PP
Returns the fee rate \- the amount of satoshi per virtual byte (a floating point
value) or undef if \f(CW\*(C`fee\*(C'\fR is undef.
.PP
NOTE: since weight of the transaction changes after signing it (due to added
signature / witness data), it is not possible to accurately measure fee rate
prior to signing.
.PP
\fIset_rbf\fR
.IX Subsection "set_rbf"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $object = $object\->set_rbf()
.Ve
.PP
Sets replace\-by\-fee for the transaction according to BIP125. The modification
of sequence number is always done on the first input. Has no effect if the
transaction already has the RBF rule.
.PP
\fIhas_rbf\fR
.IX Subsection "has_rbf"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $bool = $object\->has_rbf()
.Ve
.PP
Returns true if the transaction is subject to replace\-by\-fee.
.PP
\fIvirtual_size\fR
.IX Subsection "virtual_size"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        my $vB_size = $object\->virtual_size()
.Ve
.PP
Returns the virtual size of the transaction (in vBytes).
.PP
\&\f(CW\*(C`virtual_size\*(C'\fR is used for fee calculations. Normal transaction data is
calculated as 1 vByte per byte and witness data is calculated as 0.25 vByte per
byte.
.PP
\fIweight\fR
.IX Subsection "weight"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        my $WU_size = $object\->weight()
.Ve
.PP
Returns the weight of the transaction (in weight units).
.PP
Similar to "virtual_size", but normal transaction data is calculated as 4 WU
per byte and witness data is calculated as 1 WU per byte.
.PP
\fIupdate_utxos\fR
.IX Subsection "update_utxos"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $object = $object\->update_utxos()
.Ve
.PP
This method accepts the transaction as confirmed by the network. It unregisters
all UTXOs it consumed and registers its own outputs as new UTXOs. This means
new transactions can be created without the need to register the new UTXOs
manually.
.PP
NOTE: it does not verify the transaction by itself.
.PP
\fIverify\fR
.IX Subsection "verify"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $object\->verify(%params)
.Ve
.PP
Verifies the transaction according to the Bitcoin consensus rules. Returns
nothing, but will throw an exception if the verification failed.
.PP
See "Known problems with transactions" in Bitcoin::Crypto::Manual.
.PP
\&\f(CW%params\fR can be any of:
.IP \(bu 4
\&\f(CW\*(C`flags\*(C'\fR
.Sp
An instance of Bitcoin::Crypto::Transaction::Flags. If not passed, full set
of consensus flags will be assumed (same as calling
"new" in Bitcoin::Crypto::Transaction::Flags with no arguments).
.IP \(bu 4
\&\f(CW\*(C`block\*(C'\fR
.Sp
Optional instance of Bitcoin::Crypto::Block \- used for locktime, sequence
and coinbase verification. If it is not passed and the transaction includes
these checks, it will still verify without an exception but a warning will be
issued.
.Sp
Including this parameter is deprecated \- call \f(CW\*(C`set_block\*(C'\fR before verifying instead.
.PP
\fIverify_standard\fR
.IX Subsection "verify_standard"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $object\->verify_standard(%params)
.Ve
.PP
Same as "verify", but assumes a full set of verification \f(CW\*(C`flags\*(C'\fR. This can
be useful to determine whether the transaction is standard and will be relayed,
as opposed to default set of flags which only validates the consensus layer
(whether the transaction can be included in a block).
.PP
\fIis_coinbase\fR
.IX Subsection "is_coinbase"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $bool = $object\->is_coinbase()
.Ve
.PP
Returns true if this transaction is coinbase: its first input has an empty
previous transaction hash. Does not check any further \- actual validation of
coinbase is done in "verify".
.PP
\fIsign\fR
.IX Subsection "sign"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $signer = $object\->sign(%args)
.Ve
.PP
This method creates a new instance of Bitcoin::Crypto::Transaction::Signer,
which can be used to build a signature for any transaction regardless of
complexity. It requires user to know what type of output you are signing, and
what the operations of the script are. For signing simple, standard
transactions, "sign_transaction" in Bitcoin::Crypto::Key::Private should be used
to sign automatically (which uses the signer class under the hood).
.PP
To understand what \f(CW%args\fR can be passed to the method, see
"Common attributes" in Bitcoin::Crypto::Transaction::Signer and
"Taproot attributes" in Bitcoin::Crypto::Transaction::Signer. In addition to
those attributes, a \f(CW\*(C`compat\*(C'\fR key can be specified as a true value if a compat
segwit output is being signed (as there is no way to detect it by looking at
the transaction).
.PP
\fIdump\fR
.IX Subsection "dump"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $text = $object\->dump()
.Ve
.PP
Returns a readable description of the transaction.
